#### Steps & Code to Reproduce
> This happens upon starting the app for some users. The encryption key is generated as random byte array, and it is stored in SharedPrefs as a Base64 String. Later on (next user session), this string is retrieved from SharedPrefs, and decoded Base64 into byte array again. - provided code sample below Is there something wrong with this approach? We can loose our SharedPrefs (and the encryptionKey) only upon Clear Data/Uninstall but then i assume that the realm files are deleted also - and this issue would not occur. *Note - it is a multi-process app, but it is ensured that Realm runs on a single process (main) #### Code Sample
java SharedPreferences localPrefs = PreferenceManager.getDefaultSharedPreferences(context);
if(localPrefs.contains(ENCRYPTION_KEY)) { keyStr = localPrefs.getString(ENCRYPTION_KEY, ""); } else { byte[] randomKey = new byte[64]; new SecureRandom().nextBytes(randomKey); keyStr = Base64.encodeToString(randomKey, Base64.DEFAULT); localPrefs.edit().putString(ENCRYPTION_KEY, keyStr).commit(); }
evRealmConfig = new RealmConfiguration.Builder() .name("filename.realm") .encryptionKey(Base64.decode(keyStr, Base64.DEFAULT)) .schemaVersion(SCHEMA_VERSION) .build();
Realm realm = Realm.getInstance(evRealmConfig); //crash occurs here
`

