RealmObject::isValid() before data binding
- Use **async** DML (Insert, Update, Delete) operations


## Background

We are using realm 1.1.1 in our production environment. But occasionally we get error report as following. A few months ago, we were using an older version (~0.88), and **NEVER** experienced this at all.

**Object is no longer managed by Realm. Has it been deleted?** The full stack can be found [here](http://crashes.to/s/1ce0d5e6a30) 
## Details

Here are the code for **models**


public class Campaign extends RealmObject {
    @PrimaryKey
    private String id;

    private RealmList<PositionedSection> sections;// PositionedSection is a RealmObject as well, and it has RealmObject properties as well

    @Index
    private Date updatedAt;


When this page opened, we'll use local cache to render the campaign list and issue a request to the backend to get the latest data models. Here's what happens when the response comes


    public void onGetCampaigns(GetCampaignsEvent event) {

        if (!event.isSuccess()) {
            handleError(event);
        } else {
            List<Campaign> campaigns = event.getCampaigns(); // This is the server response
            campaignDAO.save(campaigns); // Save to the realm, will be explained later
            if(adapter != null) {
                adapter.notifyDataSetChanged();
            }

        }

    }


Here's the persistence layer code. A few things are accomplished
- Preserve the local states
- Remove and cascade-remove all the revelant properties objects.
- Save the new stuff in cascade.


    public void save(final List items) {
        Map<String, Campaign> campaignMap = new HashMap<>();
        RealmResults result = list();
        Iterator<Campaign> iter = result.iterator();
        while (iter.hasNext()) {
            Campaign temp = iter.next();
            campaignMap.put(temp.getId(), temp);
        }

        for (int i = 0; i < items.size(); i++) {
            Campaign c = (Campaign) items.get(i);
            c.saveLocalState(campaignMap.get(c.getId()));
        }

        realm.executeTransaction(new Realm.Transaction() {

            @Override
            public void execute(Realm realm) {
                for(Class temp: cascadeRemoval) {
                    realm.delete(temp);
                }
                realm.delete(type);
                realm.copyToRealmOrUpdate(items);

            }
        });

    }


Concerning the Adapter, we are using a standard RealmBaseAdapter. 

Thanks in advance.
## Updates on 2016/11/24

Here's the code for the adapter


        @Override
        public View getView(int position, View convertView, ViewGroup parent) {
            ViewHolder holder;
            if (convertView == null) {
                convertView = LayoutInflater.from(parent.getContext()).inflate(R.layout.view_campaign_item, parent, false);
                holder = new ViewHolder();
                holder.campaignStatusIcon = (ImageView) convertView.findViewById(R.id.campaign_status_icon);
                holder.campaignName = (TextView) convertView.findViewById(R.id.campaign_name);
                holder.campaignPeriod = (TextView) convertView.findViewById(R.id.campaign_period);
                holder.campaignStatusText = (TextView) convertView.findViewById(R.id.campaign_status_text);
                holder.statusLayout = (FrameLayout) convertView.findViewById(R.id.status_layout);
                convertView.setTag(holder);
            } else {
                holder = (ViewHolder) convertView.getTag();
            }

            if (!getAdapterData().isValid()) { // Countermeasure for the exception
                return convertView;
            }

            Campaign c = getItem(position);
            if (!c.isValid()) { // Countermeasure for the exception
                return convertView;
            }

            bind(convertView.getContext(), holder, c);


            return convertView;
        }



