java
RealmResults<Person> persons = realm.allObjects(Person.class);
realm.beginTransaction();
for (int i = 0; persons.size(); i++) {
	// Will only delete half the elements due to size() calling
	// sync_if_needed.
	persons.get(i).removeFromRealm(); 
 }
realm.commitTransaction();


Then we added #2990 to make sure the `RealmResults` gets updated in very next event loop by calling `handler.postAtFrontOfQueue()`. 

Usually above works fine, this becomes a topic again for below reasons:

#### 1. However there are still corner cases which could trigger an exception:

> java.lang.IllegalStateException: Object is no longer managed by Realm. Has it been deleted?

eg.: Delete an element in `RealmResults` then calling the corresponding `ListView.measure()` method. `measure()` will try to get views by calling adapter's `getView()` to measure, but at this time, since it is still in the same event loop the elements get deleted, the `RealmResults` has not been updated yet.

#### 2. PR #3834 met some difficulties to support the exact same behavior with OS `Results`.

`Results` will sync the `TableView` when ever any accessor called unless it is an snapshot.

#### 3. `RealmList` has some different behaviors compared with `RealmResults`. for example: When deleting an object in the collection, size of `RealmList` becomes the original size - 1, but the size of `RealmResults` stays the same.

### `Results::snapshot()`

This call returns a special `Results` object that never updates to reflect changes in the underlying data.

Since `Results` can be created on `Query`/`LinkView`/`TableView`, so a snapshot can be created from those as well.

### Possible solutions

#### 1. Change all `RealmResults`'s  backend to a snapshot when `beginTransaction()` called. 
And change them back in the very next event loop. This could allow us to make #3834 and stay with current `RealmResults`'s behaviors.
But this won't solve the problem 2 and 3.

#### 2. Introduce a new `RealmCollection` type `RealmSnapshotCollection`. 

`RealmSnapshotCollection` is backed by a snapshot of OS `Results`. So the collection itself won't be updated, size and order stay the same forever (elements inside are still live objects.).
It could be created by `RealmResults.snapshot()` or `RealmList.snapshot()`.
Since it won't be auto-updated, so there is no point to allow listener related APIs on it. Calling `addChangeListener` will just throw.
The iteration (both simple loop and foreach loop) will be always stable.
It is supposed to be used when the `RealmCollection`'s size and order will be changed. Take the top example again, with `RealmSnapshotCollection`, it will be implemented as:

java
RealmResults<Person> persons = realm.allObjects(Person.class);
RealmSnapshotCollection<Person> snapshot = persons.snapshot();
realm.beginTransaction();
for (int i = 0; snapshot.size(); i++) {
       // Will reach all the element in the query results since snapshot is stable.
	snapshot.get(i).removeFromRealm(); 
 }
realm.commitTransaction();

log(persons.size()) // = 0, The RealmResults is always alive
log(snapshot.size()) // = original size.
`

